ed some of the post-war tests they faced, such as demobilisation, repatriation, and fighting the widespread effects of the Spanish flu, the racial, social, political and economic hallmarks of their imperialism set the scene for a wide range of expressions of loyalties and disloyalties, and anticolonial movements. The book documents and conceptualises this 1918–20 ‘moment’ and its characteristics as a crucial three-year period of transformation for and within the Empire, examining these years for the significant shifts in the imperial relationship that occurred and as laying the foundation for later change in the imperial system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWorld War, 1914-1918zGreat BritainxInfluence. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2022. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aArmistice.  aBritish Empire.  aFirst World War.  aPeace.  aRepatriation.  aSortie de guerre.  aWar.  aimperialism.1 aBonnerjee, Samraghni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCourtois, Charles-Philippe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFathi, Romain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFathi, Romain, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarris, Trevor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHouot, Clothilde, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutchison, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutchison, Margaret, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aImy, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMawdsley, Hannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPanayi, Panikos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabula